{"_id":"1wDPwmYHycHkdBls","name":"Jewel of the Deep","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Jewel of the Deep</h1>\n<p>The characters are sailing through Kraken Bay when they chance upon a floating derelict. A terrible monster lurks aboard. But the treasure it guards is far more dangerous, for concealed within it is an entity that hungers to control men like puppets.</p>\n<p>This tale works best when there are more lives at stake, perhaps while the characters are aboard a passenger ship or hired on as mercenaries for some merchant vessel. This will also work best in the Scions Sea or Kraken Bay.</p>\n<h2>Background</h2>\n<p>Sixty years before, <em>Daughter of Cyre</em> left Cyre for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}. Aboard was the Overlord of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cyre]{Cyre's} youngest daughter and all her worldly goods, for she and her dowry had been promised to the ruler of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}. Unfortunately, <em>Daughter of Cyre</em> was separated from its escort during a great storm and never made port. Many assume she sank with all hands, though others have long speculated that she was attacked and scuttled by pirates.</p>\n<p>Many Cyreans know the name of <em>Daughter of Cyre</em> and the great treasure lost along with the lovely young woman, although her beauty and the amount of wealth she carried with her have likely grown in the intervening years. Allegedly she carried chests gleaming with a riot of gems and gold, and great heaps of pearls. What no one knows is that there was yet another passenger aboard <em>Daughter of Cyre</em>, an ancient entity who feeds upon the minds of men.</p>\n<p>At rest, with its illusion fully in place, the death jewel resembles a golden chest about two feet long, set with cloudy jewels. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cyre]{Cyre's} Overlord of two generations ago was well-acquainted with its power, having drawn it from the sealed vaults deep in Cyre where ancient spells held it in thrall. He intended to unleash it upon the aristocracy of Karrnath.</p>\n<p>Fortunately for the people of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}, <em>Daughter of Cyre</em> sank with all hands, and after a long while the case housing the creature rotted enough that its sorcerous wards failed and the being crept free. Now it hungers.</p>\n<p>A sapphire ring mixed in with the treasures remaining aboard ship grants immunity to the creature’s assaults—it was intended to have been worn by the Overlord’s daughter, who would have used her immunity to assume command of the kingdom and welcome Cyrean wizards from across the Inner Sea to quell “the sorcerous plague”—in reality the attacks unleashed by the entity.</p>\n<p>As the adventure begins, the entity has just depleted decades worth of stored sorcerous strength to raise the derelict from where it rests, so it can enter the world of men and feed. It is particularly eager to wreak vengeance on the people of Cyre.</p>\n<h2>The Derelict</h2>\n<p>As their ship crosses the Inner Sea one misty morning the characters spy the masts of another vessel looming through the fog. As the characters draw closer they notice that the ship lacks canvas, and many of the spars are broken and hang at odd angles. Moreover, the ship is absolutely silent—there’s no one talking or moving aboard, and certainly no one there answers hails.</p>\n<p>If the characters draw within a few hundred feet, the fog’s thin enough to see there’s no one aboard. Seaweed and other vegetable matter clings to the listing vessel, and portions of the rail and prow are broken away. She rides low, as though she’s taken on water, but she doesn’t seem to be sinking.</p>\n<p>A Knowledge (Naval history) or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} (−2) roll reveals that the ship appears of an older make, a Cyrean merchant with a high prow and forecastle of a sort that was popular generations ago.</p>\n<p>The name on the prow is partly obscured by grime and muck, but astute characters can make out the name <em>Daughter of Cyre</em> after a little bit of study, and any Cyrean who makes a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} roll is aware of the vessel’s sad history and reputed treasure. Characters who wish to board should probably take a rowboat over. A soggy ladder is built into <em>Daughter of Cyre’s</em> starboard side, on the other side of the vessel from the characters. If they don’t circle the ship before boarding they have to toss over lines, or climb up themselves.</p>\n<p>If the characters do circle the ship, with a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} (−2) they see there’s a long rent in the ship above the waterline near the prow, right about where the forward cargo bay would be. The detail is hidden by the fog and draped seaweed.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Image:</span> @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Derelict Ship]{Derelict Ship}</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Boarding the Daughter of Cyre</h2>\n<p>The deck is hidden under a coat of seaweed and other detritus, where expiring fish lay goggle-eyed and twitching. The timbers of the ship itself are soggy and the planks creak, though they are sturdy enough to support the characters. The ship’s boats are aboard and rotting, so whatever happened didn’t give anyone a chance to get away. Worse, a character who succeeds on a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll hears an occasional scrabbling sound from belowdecks. Something down there is moving, although the sound stops before they can get a clear fix on where it is.</p>\n<p>There’s nothing on the main deck that’s remotely worth salvaging. There are rotten barrels and moldering rope and rusted winches and gyves, and a whole lot of smelly, dying sea life.</p>\n<p>There’s not much to see above decks. Now that the characters are aboard they can better tell that the deck house is badly damaged and missing most of its roof. Only the captain’s cabin is relatively intact.</p>\n<h3>The Captain’s Cabin</h3>\n<p>The door hangs ajar, and creaks as it’s opened wide enough for the characters to investigate the fish-scented darkness. The moment they step in farther or shine light within, a tentacle sways up from behind the shattered wreck of the captain’s table. An octopus lies dying behind the furniture, and perishes before it can do much more than frighten the characters.</p>\n<p>The cabin is a complete shambles, but there are chests to open. Two are waterlogged and contain moldy rags that were once clothing. A third contains half-a-dozen bottles of wine, still sealed, each worth 50 golden galifars, white wine of the famed Ketner and Mohr vineyards.</p>\n<p>There’s a wreck of a desk built into one bulkhead. Rolled-up maps shoved into cubbyholes above the desk have long since disintegrated to all but useless pulp. Hidden in the desk drawers in a locked drawer is an eelskin pouch, tightly sealed. The lock itself is not especially complex, but it’s rusty and the wood is swollen, so characters must either succeed at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} (−2) or break in with brute force (the desk has a Toughness of 6).</p>\n<p>Characters familiar with sea travel can make @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} rolls to be aware of expensive eelskin pouches, which are designed to keep important documents watertight.</p>\n<p>The captain’s log book is within. A few generations of submersion have managed to get through even the fine eelskin and the log book’s quite moist. It remains intact, though, and if carefully dried, the final pages, midway through the journal, can be read. A successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Smarts} roll should suggest this if the players themselves don’t realize this. Trying to read the information now will simply destroy it.</p>\n<p>All else within the captain’s cabin is sodden and rotting.</p>\n<h3>The Main Hold</h3>\n<p>A ladderless hole leads down to the main hold, so characters must either drop a rope and climb down, or make an @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Agility} roll to land safely. Within is more dead sea, mostly smaller fish, although there’s one struggling sea turtle. A few crabs crawl here and there when light is shone upon them. Up near the prow is a metal door with a complex lock.</p>\n<p>The characters hear the clatter of a large thing on the other side of the door, clumping around on the deck planks. It sounds like nothing they’ve ever heard before—unless they’ve ever seen an eight-legged horse with a limp ridden by someone playing castanets.</p>\n<h3>The Vault</h3>\n<p>There are three ways into the vault.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the starboard side of the ship, opposite the character’s vessel, is a man-sized gash that opens up to the chamber. The characters had a chance to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} this if they inspected the ship before boarding.</li>\n<li>The wood on either side of the door can be chopped through fairly easily (Toughness 8). Being at the bottom of the ocean has softened it.</li>\n<li>The lock can be picked, although this isn’t easy. In addition to having multiple tumblers it’s also rusty. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} attempts are made at −6.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once the characters can see inside, they spy dozens of large chests and cabinets and dressers lashed to the walls or lying on the deck. Their ruined contents lie strewn upon the planking. Perhaps those rotting clumps used to be silken finery or draperies or bedroom linens.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Your attention is held by the clacking monstrosity that looms out of the darkness, a monstrous crab that stands half again as tall as a man. It scuttles toward you, reaching with both its claws.</p>\n</aside>\n<ul>\n<li>Giant Crab (1)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once the giant crab is defeated the treasure can be examined. The cases were once enormously expensive wood carvings, gilt with gold and silver, but they’re quite ruined. So are all the furniture and a fortune in what probably was clothing and linens.</p>\n<p>However, one chest contains gold gilt dinnerware and another, smaller chest holds fine jewelry. A third thick wooden chest is covered with detailed symbols. Anyone with @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} can, with a successful roll, recognize these symbols as magical sigils, and tell that the rot and wet has eaten through the sigils so they’re no longer effective. A raise on the roll enables a character to recognize those sigils for particularly potent warding spells.</p>\n<p>Breaking through this chest requires three @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls to avoid three jabbing needles—which will frighten rather than harm, for the once deadly poison has been soaked up by the wood surrounding the needle. More observant characters can @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} by the state of the chest that it’s rotten and that it’s probably possible to pry, hack, or even kick it open.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Inside on long rotted cloth is a very small chest that’s a work of art in itself, studded with rubies and sapphires. It has no obvious lock or hinges, and on closer examination you wonder if it’s no chest, but solid gold.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>It’s likely far more valuable as is than it would be melted down and pried apart. A successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} (−1) roll determines it could fetch upward of 3,000 golden galifars or more.</p>\n<p>This is the death jewel, and it has nearly exhausted its sorcerous ability to keep the derelict afloat. Once it’s picked up, the ship begins to list. From below is a loud pop and the ship promptly sinks into the water. If the characters climbed down (or up, through the gash) a rope, they can reach the top deck in four rounds; the water reaches the weather deck in six rounds, and the ship is completely submerged in eight.</p>\n<p>This should be run as a dramatic task. With @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} being rolled to grab treasure. 4 successes on these need to be rolled before a character will peel themselves away from grabbing treasure. Those who succeed can support others to try and pull them away.</p>\n<p>It is difficult, if not impossible, to escape with the entirety of the treasure glimpsed in the vault. It requires two sailors to carry either chest at a slow walking pace owing to their weight, and with the ship taking on water most characters are liable to simply grab a few handfuls of gold or necklaces or a gem-studded goblet.</p>\n<p>Roll [[/r 2d6]] for every character to determine the overall worth of whatever they managed to lay hands on, then multiply by 300. The result is the value of the object in rilks. Don’t skimp on the description. For instance: A diamond ring patterned with fish scales, an emerald studded goblet, a gold chalice, a gold dinner plate with the Overlord’s family crest stamped along the rim, a pearl necklace, a slim gold chain hung with a gleaming ruby, a tarnished beaker gilt with exquisite gold leaf showing swimming mermaids, etc.</p>\n<p>One of the characters should acquire a sapphire ring, the shanks of which are decorated with the image of a tower shield. It has been specially crafted to shield its wearer from mental assaults of the creature.</p>\n<h2>The Log Book</h2>\n<p>Extremely careful examination of the log book enables those reading it to get to the material in the middle. The opening pages and the blank back pages are too sodden to pry apart. Ideally, the characters should discover the information at the log book as the death jewel’s plans get underway—perhaps they feel the ship lurching under their feet as the controlled crew alters the vessel’s course.</p>\n<p>Most of the journal entries are mundane discussions of weather, but the captain writes occasional cryptic references about the cargo and how he was told he should clear away from the city if he valued his own safety. He seems fond of the Overlord’s daughter and asked her if she were in any danger, and she reported to him that all would be well so long as she wore the sapphire ring.</p>\n<p>The last entry reads almost like a confessional. The captain spent a heady night with the Overlord’s daughter and she told him the entire plot—how the entity controlled the minds of men, how the Overlord intended it to wreak havoc upon the aristocracy of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Karrnath]{Karrnath}, and how she promised to make him her consort once she ruled the city. She also made mention of the ring’s power.</p>\n<h2>The Creature Moves</h2>\n<p>Once it’s safely aboard the heroes’ ship and attention is diverted from it, the creature’s gemstones clear and it begins to work its will. It means to return to Cyre as swiftly as possible and lay its eggs within the Overlord. It has little conception of or interest in the lifespan of humanity and is perfectly happy to take its vengeance upon the dead Overlord’s descendants.</p>\n<p>It’s first concern is to be free, having developed a strong distaste for enclosed spaces after long years, so it controls the nearest human and has it carry it about so it can see what’s happening. It does not like being stored in a chest or other container and definitely prefers to be carted around in someone’s arms.</p>\n<p>If there are Extras aboard the death jewel immediately sets them to raising full sails and altering course. It can control up to two dozen characters at a time, although owing to their sapped will and delayed movement any skill or attribute checks function at −4. Extras are assumed to fail.</p>\n<p>Characters can resist the creature’s control by making a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Spirit} roll once per day. Unless they’re aware of the creature, they are unlikely to know what’s going on, and may assume that they’ve simply had a mild dizzy spell. The death jewel can control someone within 100 feet, even outside of sight range.</p>\n<p>Once ensorcelled, characters can attempt to break free of its spell with another @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Spirit} roll if they have harmed someone they care about or are actively engaged in something suicidal, or if the creature itself has taken damage.</p>\n<p>The entity communicates only through the humans it controls and doesn’t articulate well. If questioned or challenged, the humans only say things like the following, which sound very strange coming from the lips of friend and colleagues.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“You will never imprison me again! Cyre will pay, and my younglings will be birthed from the Overlord’s flesh!”</p>\n<p>“The Overlord meant to send me away, but I will have my vengeance!”</p>\n<p>“You humans are nothing but cattle. I shall steer you all and my children shall feed upon you.”</p>\n</aside>\n<p>It is rather blunt in its machinations, and attempts to kill those it cannot control. It tries to use those it can to protect itself. Those who resist the creature face a greater challenge in avoiding hurting their friends and allies than actually killing the terrible thing.</p>\n<h2>Aftermath</h2>\n<p>Once the creature is killed, all affected characters recover their own will. Those who were controlled by the creature only have a hazy, dream-like memory of actions they performed under its power.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_slwk1t4xhcl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"260fKdr6NlF3cscp","name":"A Night Forgotten","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">A Night Forgotten</h1>\n<p>All the following options revolve around your would-be pirate being in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}, and the circumstances that brought you to the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} tavern.  Your unfortunate night at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} has you running afoul of a press gang from the pirate ship <em>Storm Reaver</em>. Choose one of the options below for your evening in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}, or come up with something along these similiar lines.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Old friend:</span> You have been searching for the right crew to join for your next adventure. Funds are low and you will need more if you are going to be able to accomplish anything for other Cyrans. A meeting with a contact had been arranged at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} in Pier's End. The meeting went well,and a few more drinks in celebration followed. A few more drinks, but surely not enough to black out...</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">The Sea Calls:</span> You came to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} in search of finding a new home now that Cyre is gone. Niether @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Sharn]{Sharn}, nor @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.New Cyre]{New Cyre}, or any of the other ghettos can rightfully be called a home. After a few drinks at the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron}, you went down to the docks to take in the view of the sea and the ships at port. The last thing you remember is a blow to the back of your head and the waves ruching up to meet you.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">A hero in cramped quarters:</span>  You were between ships in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}, and after stopping for a drink at a tavern called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron}, you happened upon a damsel in distress in the alleyway outside. Thinking you could help, you didn’t notice the thugs hiding nearby, and they caught you unawares. You’ve been on enough ships to know a press gang by the blow of the sap on the back of your neck. You just hope whatever ship you end up on has a respectable captain.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Wasted plunder:</span>  You found yourself relatively well off when you got your share of your last voyage’s plunder, and decided to spend a few of your hard-won coins at @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron}, a popular sailor tavern in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport}. Maybe the shine of your new wealth distracted you, however, because you never saw the miscreants who slipped something into your drink, knocking you out cold.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Nothing like a good tavern brawl:</span> The atmosphere of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} has always been to your liking. Boisterious, lively, folk of the sea, a little bit shady, and you have always loved the cats there. Last night was another lively night. After a few drinks last night, you found yourself uncharacteristically joining into a brawl that started. Though you handled yourself well and just defending your new life long friend's honor. As you staggered around the corner to relieve yourself, you were set upon by a group of rough-looking thugs. They overwhlemed you and knocked you unconscious. At least you hope you did soil your pants.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Arawai's Blessing:</span>  You came to a tavern in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} in search of your fate or maybe just another ship to join. You’re not sure how many drinks you had, but they quickly went to your head and you passed out on the table before you found your destiny—unless it lay in the bottom of a bottle. Then again, maybe you found your destiny after all...</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Barron Tailspinner:</span>  You went to a tavern called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron} in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} to earn a few coins with your tales of the sea. The patrons seemed pleased with your performance and bought you a few drinks. You had just remembered a tale of an unfortunate sailor who found himself press-ganged on a pirate ship after his drink was drugged when suddenly everything went black.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Cabin Fever:</span> It took you a few months to sail here from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Sharn]{Sharn} aboard the <em>Tiger Princess</em>. That was way too long to be at sea without any stops. You arrived here in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} almost a week ago, and you are finally starting to feel like you have made up for the time lost on the <em>Tiger Princess</em>. One more night at a new spot wouldn't hurt. You heard numerous good rumors about the ale and games at the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Salty Dog and The Baron]{the Salty Dog and The Baron}, and so it was time to check it out. You promised yourself this night you would only have one drink and have your wits about you to finally remeber what you can learn about what is happening in this city. You don't remember anything after that first drink.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_sfbrzx24rkb","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Player Character Guide","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"276jgwCRrWKYcf0I","name":"04 Skeleton Crew","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Skeleton Crew</h1>\n<p>At dawn, a few hours after the celebration finally winds down, the ship’s bell sounds, calling all hands on deck. When the crew is assembled, a long line of captured officers and sailors from the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> is brought on deck and paraded before the crew. Prince Rockface addresses the captives first, offering a place on the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> crew for any who want to throw their lot in with pirates. Several of the Rahadoumi sailors step forward; Master Scourge cuts their bonds, and the sailors take their places among the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> crew. Prince Rockface then turns to address the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> crew.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“All right, you scurvy tars! You’ve done a right good job by me—we’ve got a second ship now, and she’s quite a prize from the looks of her. But I still have only one crew. So here’s the plan—the <em>Storm Reaver</em> will sail on to our planned destination with our new shipmates here, while Mister Lagraa will pick a skeleton crew to sail the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> to Port Krez, where she’ll be worth a pretty penny as salvage.</p>\n<p>“As for these fine fellows here”—Prince Rockface gestures at the remainder of the captured ship’s crew—“some of them will no doubt be worth a hefty ransom from their families back in Breland. And for the rest, if the life of a pirate’s not for them, they can spend the rest of their lives at sea!”</p>\n</aside>\n<p>To make her point, Prince Rockface grabs one of the Brelish sailors and throws her overboard to the accompaniment of cheers and laughter from the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> crew. As the unfortunate woman sinks beneath the waves, many of the remaining sailors scramble to swear their loyalty to Prince Rockface. The officers are led belowdecks and the crew begins to disperse to their daily tasks.</p>\n<p>As they do, Mister Lagraa and Master Scourge pick out several of the <em>Storm Reaver's</em> original crew, telling them to be aboard the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> within 10 minutes to set sail for Port Krez. The swabs are chosen to join the skeleton crew as well, and Scourge smiles evilly at them as he picks them. The swabs have little time left on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, but allow them to gather whatever gear or loot they may have acquired, and give them one last chance to purchase supplies from the quartermaster’s store. If any of the swabs have befriended Cut-Throat Grok, she cries as they leave. If she was made helpful, she gives them a gift worth 100 gp from the stores on parting.</p>\n<p>The skeleton crew of the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> includes the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Mister Lagraa (now Captain)</li>\n<li>Master Scourage (now First Mate)</li>\n<li>Patch \"Salty\" Kolkrinun</li>\n<li>Krornik \"Fishguts\" Kragshard</li>\n<li>Owlbear Hartshorn</li>\n<li>The rest of the original crew of the <em>Storm Reaver</em>.</li>\n<li>The swabs</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>New Ship, Harsher Discipline</h2>\n<p>As the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> sets sail, acting captain Mister Lagraa and her first mate Master Scourge gather the crew together to inform them that although this is a new ship, the rules are the same, though discipline on the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> will be a good deal harsher than on the lackadaisical <em>Storm Reaver</em>— all crimes are now punishable with the cat instead of the whip. All of the crew keep the same jobs they had before on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>, but they will have to work a good deal harder, as the crew is smaller.</p>\n<p><strong>Fatigue: </strong>From now on all checks to avoid @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} on the ship are made at a -2 penalty. Tasks that did not have a Vigor check for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}, now require a Vigor check.</p>\n<p>Master Scourge ensures that the swabs continue to have the worst jobs of the crew for the remainder of this journey (you should assign the swabs the worst duties or the duties they most hate every day rather than rolling randomly). As night falls, the sails of the <em>Storm Reaver</em> disappear over the horizon. Mister Lagraa does not believe in crew entertainment or rum rations, and anyone caught above decks after dusk without leave gets six lashes with the cat. At your discretion, gambling might still go on belowdecks, but it is quite likely that Mister Lagraa and Scourge will hear about it and act accordingly.</p>\n<h3>New Destination</h3>\n<p>That night, Mister Lagraa, Scourge, and those pirates loyal to them hold a secret meeting in the captain’s cabin, where they plot to sail the ship not to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Port Krez]{Port Krez}, but to a dry dock in Cliff's End called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Rickety's Squibs]{Rickety's Squibs}, where they can make the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> their own and engage in piracy for themselves. Mister Lagraa and Scourge want only the most loyal crew with them, however, and plan to do away with the swabs and their friends as soon as Rickety’s Squibs is in sight. </p>\n<p>Friendly crew members begin whispering their concerns to the swabs by the second day of the voyage. If the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> is sailing back to Port Krez, what is to become of the group of press-ganged crew? Rumors begin to spread among the friendly crew members that Mister Lagraa might decide to claim the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> for himself and establish himself as a pirate captain in his own right. These rumors become more certain when a friendly cremember deduces (if the swabs haven’t already) that the ship has changed course and is heading west past @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Tidewater Rock]{Tidewater Rock} and into Cliff's End. If the swabs have not considered staging a mutiny themselves, friendly crewmembers begin making that suggestion for them, but only when the time is right. </p>\n<p>During the evening, Kragshard suggests to the swabs that he knows where the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> might be heading—to a seedy, isolated dry dock in Cliff's End called @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Rickety's Squibs]{Rickety's Squibs}. For a price, old Rickety Hake completely refits ships into “squibs,” providing new identities by changing ships’ lines, silhouettes, and general appearance to be unrecognizable to their former owners or anyone else familiar with them.</p>\n<h2>New Destination and Another Storm</h2>\n<p>Within a day or so the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> will clearly start heading south west instead of west. As it nears @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Tidewater Rock]{Tidewater Rock} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Traglorn Island]{Traglorn Island} a storm will hit the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> in the early hours of the morning. The <em>Majestic Griffon</em> is blown way off course and all hands are call to work on the deck. All hands are required to work in the rigging, given random @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tables.Rigging Tasks}]{Rigging Tasks}. </p>\n<p>As the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> struggles off course, a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} check at –2 for swabs to see the dark shapes loom out of the sea all around the ship. Small islets and coral reefs that dot this area. The storm is fierce being the equivelant of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Dark illumination}.</p>\n<p>At this point a few grindylows will board the ship and make off with a couple of tasty sailors, Sandara Quinn among them. Emboldened by their success more grindylows attack the beleaguered ship for more food. They flee when half or more of them have been slain.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Grindylow]{Grindylow} (6)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Shipwrecked</h2>\n<p>As the storm begins to abate, the <em>Majestic Griffon</em> hits the coral reefs surrounding @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Bonewreck Isle]{Bonewreck Isle} and runs aground. As the sun rises and the tide goes out, the members of the crew slowly come to terms with their predicament. The <em>Majestic Griffon</em> is holed in the main hold. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating} or @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} check is enough to surmise that although the ship is not in immediate danger of sinking, she’ll eventually sink unless repairs are made. Mister Lagraa immediately instructs several of the crew to begin dismantling the ship’s deck to repair the vessel.</p>\n<p>Early in the morning, Mister Lagraa calls the roll of the crew, and two of the ship’s sailors are discovered to be missing. One of the missing crew members is Sandara Quinn; the other should be chosen randomly from among those pirates most friendly to the swabs. Mister Lagraa is dismissive of the two pirates’ fate.</p>\n<p>At the same time, the crew discovers that the ship’s water barrel burst when the vessel ran aground and is now empty. Mister Lagraa orders the swabs to take one of the ship’s cutters and a couple of empty barrels and find fresh water and supplies on the nearby island. She tells the swabs that the ship will depart when repairs are done, whether they are back or not.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_n10pg472em","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"29ph4ljQMFyaXUCp","name":"Jiran ir'Gazan","content":"<div>\n<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p>the Storm Songstress. Former general of Cyre. Spent her early life in the Shield mountains, learning the ways of the stormsingers, then served in the military. Became a general. Wrote an anthology called “The Seven Scrolls of the Mindful Soldier”, a treatise of philosophy and musings on the ethics of war. Retired in 985 after losing two sons to the War, now lives in an idyllic, secluded countryside retreat [somewhere, possibly Dragon Peaks?]. I think she could serve as our ship’s Mage, summoning winds to fill the sails and lightning to batter our enemies. She retired because of the personal loss of her children–maybe letting her know every Cyran survivor now shares her burden might rouse the ex-general back to service.</p>\n<p>By now, Jiran’s an old woman. Human, caucasian, lithe, with a face weathered by age. Long, wispy white hair that dances in the wind. Specializes in Fighting (Unarmed combat and Glaive), Battle (Military command), and Spellcasting (Lightning &amp; Wind spells)</p>\n<p>That she'd retreated to some idyllic mountain hermitage up in the Endworld Mountains of Q'barra; a real monastery-type place, according to rumor. Probably even had monks doing pilgrimages and stuff for her tutelage. I think she just wanted to get away from people, but maybe her connection to storms and weather made that an easier reality to attain than going all the way to, say, Adar.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","img":"modules/monks-enhanced-journal/assets/person.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"person","relationships":[],"role":"","location":"Endworld Mountains, Q'Barra","race":"Human","gender":"Female","age":"","pronoun":"She/Her","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","_lasttab":"description","fields":{"race":{"value":true},"gender":{"value":true},"age":{"value":true},"eyes":{"value":true},"skin":{"value":false},"hair":{"value":true},"pronoun":{"value":true},"profession":{"value":true},"voice":{"value":true},"faction":{"value":false},"height":{"value":false},"weight":{"value":false},"traits":{"value":true},"ideals":{"value":false},"bonds":{"value":false},"flaws":{"value":true},"longterm":{"value":true},"shortterm":{"value":true},"beliefs":{"value":true},"secret":{"value":true}},"scrollPos":"{\".tab.details .tab-inner\":0,\".tab.description .tab-inner\":0,\".relationships .items-list\":0}"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{"type":"person"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6nu2k3j5j03","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar Lore#/CF_SEP/Lhazaar Principalities#/CF_SEP/02.09.12. People#/CF_SEP/Potential Crew","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"2yORFTp4VWtGqFGZ","name":"#[CF_tempEntity]","content":"","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_6flk4g3q5af","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Images#/CF_SEP/Misc","color":"#000000","name":"Misc","children":["7wWl7nPjg13IDQma","5pA0Rst2Ho7fd1Fi"],"folderPath":["temp_bmn52t4oyo","temp_i1dpvu9m1i"]}}}
{"_id":"34EWHb1shCISVITk","name":"Jurian Bartell","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p>(m human, late 40s). Lt. Jurian Bartell (formerly of the House Deneith 85th) is Aundairan by birth, but as far as he is concerned, Cyre will always be home. He always has a tall tale or witty quip in reply to anyone who asks about how that came to be. Jurian appreciates the finer things in life, especially if they come in a bottle, and had been quietly helping Daina learn the social niceties he knew she would need to match her new name once the war was over and she and Mazello returned to Metrol. Daina left Jurian a note saying goodbye when she deserted.</p>\n<p>Jurian is light on his feet and prefers to disorient his opponents with cutting words wherever possible. He is quick to smile and is something of a social butterfly, though that smile may or may not always be sincere.</p>\n<p>When Daina was in Sharn she often hung out at a tavern frequented by the local Deneith people, and in 996 overheard some of them swapping stories making the rounds about some smartass former Blackblade who dressed like a Cyran, spoke with a heavy Aundarian accent, and was apparently now beholden to neither of those nations as he was now an instructor at Rekkenmark and had the ear of King Kaius himself. Their description made it sound like Jurian, but as a deserter she was too afraid to ask.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/monks-enhanced-journal/assets/person.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"person","relationships":[{"type":"organization","id":"pnBZ8R4fkTBwT4Um","relationship":"Part of the Blademarks Guild","hidden":false}],"role":"","location":"Unknown","race":"human","gender":"Male","age":"48","pronoun":"He/Him","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"","voice":"","faction":"House Deneith","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","_lasttab":"description","fields":{"race":{"value":true},"gender":{"value":true},"age":{"value":true},"eyes":{"value":true},"skin":{"value":false},"hair":{"value":true},"pronoun":{"value":true},"profession":{"value":false},"voice":{"value":true},"faction":{"value":true},"height":{"value":false},"weight":{"value":false},"traits":{"value":true},"ideals":{"value":false},"bonds":{"value":false},"flaws":{"value":true},"longterm":{"value":false},"shortterm":{"value":false},"beliefs":{"value":false},"secret":{"value":false}},"scrollPos":"{\".tab.details .tab-inner\":0,\".tab.description .tab-inner\":0,\".relationships .items-list\":0}"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{"type":"person"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6nu2k3j5j03","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar Lore#/CF_SEP/Lhazaar Principalities#/CF_SEP/02.09.12. People#/CF_SEP/Potential Crew","color":"#000000"}}}
