{"_id":"OFdQGATN7TtJNvRX","name":"01 Welcome to the Storm Reaver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Welcome to the Storm Reaver</h1>\n<p>The pirates wake up the in the hold of Prince Rockface's the <em>Storm Reaver</em> of the @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cloudreaver Principality]{Cloudreaver Principality}. They all remember the night before, but they all blacked out at some point. The pirates awake feeling groggy like they are still hung over. Before the pirates can do much more than sit up, Master Scourge enters the hold to wake them and get them up to the main deck. Six rough-looking <em>Storm Reaver</em> pirates, armed with saps, accompany him. An expression that might be mistaken for pain but which is clearly an attempt at a smile bruises Scourge's face as he cracks the whip in his hand and screams at newcomers.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Still abed with the sun over the yardarm? On your feet, ye filthy swabs! Get up on deck and report for duty afore Prince Rockface flays your flesh into sausage skins and has Fishguts fry ye up for breakfast!”</p>\n</aside>\n<p>The pirates quickly discover that most, if not all, of their weapons and equipment are gone. If the any refuse, even momentarily, to accompany Scourge, he lashes out at any offender with his whip. If necessary, he calls for aid from his crew, who attack uncooperative characters with their saps. It should be immediately clear that if they don't cooperate, they will quickly be overpowered. </p>\n<p><strong>Development:</strong> If the pirates decide to fight, Master Scourge and his pirates attack subduing them. The <em>Storm Reaver</em> pirates will not the kill the new comers, however. Once they have the upper hand, they will take the offender—conscious or unconscious—to the main deck, where they get an immediate taste of @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{punishment} on the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. The offenders are tied to the mainmast, and Master Scourge gives each of them three lashes before the captain's address.</p>\n<p class=\"example\"><strong>Skill Check:</strong> On the way to the upper deck, have the pirates make notice checks. On a <strong>success </strong>they hear someone making oinking sounds and talking soothingly to was sounds like a pig. On a raise someon hears the rattle of a chain, and a slight whimper.</p>\n<h2>Meeting the Captain</h2>\n<p>Once on the main deck it's quickly apparent that they are on a sizable ship in the middle of the ocean, far from any land. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Regalport]{Regalport} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Greentarn]{Greentarn} are just an ochre haze many miles astern. Figures cluster around the ship's mainmast, looking up at the higher deck on the stern, where two figures stand, Prince Rockface and First Mate Mister Lagraa.</p>\n<p>There are three other recruits are standing with them on the deck, set apart by their relative cleanliness and their apparent unease with their newfound situation. The other three were picked up in Elysium, Sandara Quinn, Rosie Cusswell, and Conchobhar Turlach Dalian. A dozen or so other pirates stand about on the deck or in the ship's rigging. Once everyone is on the main deck, the captain speaks.</p>\n<aside class=\"sidebar read-aloud\">\n<p>“Glad you could join us at last! Welcome to the <em>Storm Reaver</em>! My thanks for ‘volunteering' to join my crew. I'm Mika Rockface. That's Prince Rockface to you filthy lot, not that you'll ever need to address me. I have only one rule—don't speak to me. I like talk, but I don't like your talk. Follow that rule and we'll all get along fine.</p>\n<p>“Oh, and one more thing. Even with you new recruits, we're still short-handed, and I aim to keep what crew I have. There'll be a keelhaulin' for anyone caught killin' anyone. Mr. Lagraa! If you'd be so kind as to make pirates out of these landlubbers, it'll save me having to put them in the sweatbox for a year and a day before I make pies out of 'em.”</p>\n</aside>\n<h2>Job Assignments</h2>\n<p>After some recent difficulties, the <em>Storm Reaver </em>is undermanned and there are some roles that need to be filled. Mister Lagraa first is looking for a new rigger. The scoundrals are all required to climb to the crows nest.</p>\n<p class=\"example\"><strong>Dramatic Task</strong> This will require 3 round Dramtic Task. @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks are the only skilled allowed. The pirate with the most success tokens is the winner is that they are now a rigger and work directly for Mister Lagraa. Anyone caught deliberately trying to fail the test will be immediately given three lashes as @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Punishments]{punishment}.</p>\n<p>Lagraa's second test is one of necessity—he knows the ship's cook, Krornik “Fishguts” Kragshard, has a drinking problem, and he's fed up with eating rubbish. This test is simple: Lagraa asks each pirate in turn whether they can cook, and if one of them says yes, theybecoe the new cook's mate. If Lagraa gets to the end of the line without an affirmative answer, he simply picks the fattest pirate (Lagraa assumes that character likes food the most) and says, “You're a cook's mate now,” and tells that PC to report to Krornik Kragshard in the galley. If more than one person claims to be a good cook, Lagraa picks the fattest.</p>\n<p>The remaining pirates are all assigned to be swabs, under the command of Master Scourge, who immediately gets them working. </p>\n<p>Review @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.A Pirate's Day]{A Pirate's Day} and @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{Ship Board Actions} to find out more what the pirates do during the day. Check the entry on @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Krornik Kragshard]{Krornik Kragshard} for interactions on the first day with Fishguts.</p>\n<h2>Friendly Face</h2>\n<p>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Sandara Quinn]{Sandara Quinn} has managed to convince @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Cut-Throat Grok]{Cut-Throat Grok} to return her personal equipment, claiming the itesm were righteous artifacts blessed by @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Arawai]{Arawai} that would bring a terrible curse on those who wrongfully held them. This morning she managed to acquire two items of the new crew members, items that they would struggle without the use of. At some point on this first day she will approach the new comers as soon as she can to return equipment and offer her friendship. She can explain the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is not what you know but who you know on a pirate ship. Friends help each other out, enemies cause trouble.</li>\n<li>She knows Prince Mika is upset as they have not had a very successful outting at sea, and once again she couldn't crack Tidewater Rock.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>A Keelhauling</h2>\n<p><strong>Work:</strong> The pirates spend the day at their assigned jobs. In addition, each pirates can take a single daytime ship action.</p>\n<p><strong>“Bloody Hour”:</strong> The crew gathers on deck at dusk to witness the keelhauling of Jakes Magpie, a pirate caught stealing from the quartermaster's store the night before. After a brief interrogation at the hands of Mr. Lagraa and Master Scourge, Jakes admitted his crime, and is now brought up from the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Bilges]{bilges} to be slowly keelhauled before the evening meal. A successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} can see the relish with which Mr. Lagraa, in particular, tugs at the rope as the unfortunate Magpie is dragged under the ship. What appears on the other side has been cut to shreds and is soon thrown overboard to feed the sharks.</p>\n<p>A pirate who examines the body before it is dumped can make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} check to estimate that the unfortunate Jakes took significant damage from the punishment and drowned as well. Witnessing Jakes's keelhauling should help impress upon the pirates the deadly nature of pirate punishments.</p>\n<p><strong>Leisure:</strong> After dinner and the rum rations, various @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Crew Entertainment]{pirate entertainments} take place on @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Main Deck]{deck}, in the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Weapons Deck]{weapons deck} or the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Mess Hall]{mess hall}, for as long as people are sober enough to participate. In addition, each pirate can take a single nighttime @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{ship action}.</p>\n<p><strong>Rest:</strong> Provided they've drunk their @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Grog Ration]{rum rations}, the pirates can retire to their hammocks in the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Weapons Deck]{weapons deck} whenever they wish. The pirates can take additional nighttime @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tales.Ship Board Actions]{ship actions} if they have the energy.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":false,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.6\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_n10pg472em","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"PH5sEmqgrKISoHfZ","name":"Revenge!","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Revenge!</h1>\n<p>No matter where the group tries to sell the necklace in Shark Bay a masaquani local, Yan Yort, oversees the sale. Without warning he lunges at the character holding the necklace, crying out,</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Murderer! Where did you get that?”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Yan doesn’t draw a weapon and should be easy to subdue.</p>\n<p>Once he has been restrained Yan breaks down.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“I gave that necklace to my girlfriend last year. She vanished two months ago. She had secretly been seeing a visitor by the name of Marcus Royal. I found out a few months ago after following her one night, but I didn’t mind. I loved her. One night she never came back. I assumed she’d left me for Royal. Please, tell me where you found it?”</p>\n</section>\n<p>After listening to the heroes’ tale Yan’s face tightens.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“She would never have thrown it away. She knew how much it was worth. Royal must have killed her! I’ll give you 1,000 pieces of eight if you help me kill him.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Royal did indeed kill the woman. She fell in love with him but Royal only wanted her for her body. After a vicious argument Royal stabbed her and threw her body in the lagoon. She had never shown him the necklace, but kept it hidden in her dress.</p>\n<p>Yan knows Royal spends most of his time in the Wench and Tankard tavern near the docks. Attacking Royal in the tavern is too risky—he has many friends—but once he leaves for his ship he is fair game. If Yan dies in the fight the heroes find $300 on his person.</p>\n<p> Yan Yort (195): Typical Pirate.</p>\n<p>Pirates (41): 40 Typical Pirates and Marcus Royal, a Wild Card Veteran Pirate (p. 195).</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_slwk1t4xhcl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Savage Tales","color":"#000000"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"Q4EF2yAAh8G7dJHd","name":"Reginald Haltraed","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> Artificer</p>\n<p><strong>Appearance (besides image):</strong> young, glasses</p>\n<p><strong>Personality: </strong>unsure of himself</p>\n<p><strong>How he met Trucco: </strong>Around the same age as Trucco, he helped him to escape from his own house after a failed attempt at robbery. They got somewhat close as children, Trucco encouraging him to feel more confident in his creations.</p>\n<p><strong>Last interaction/rumor: </strong>He went to school to become a proper Artificer and became a prodigy for his age, some say he was involved in whatever caused The Mourning.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/monks-enhanced-journal/assets/person.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"person","relationships":[],"role":"","location":"","race":"","gender":"","age":"","pronoun":"","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","_lasttab":"details","fields":{"race":{"value":true},"gender":{"value":true},"age":{"value":true},"eyes":{"value":true},"skin":{"value":false},"hair":{"value":true},"pronoun":{"value":true},"profession":{"value":true},"voice":{"value":true},"faction":{"value":false},"height":{"value":false},"weight":{"value":false},"traits":{"value":true},"ideals":{"value":false},"bonds":{"value":false},"flaws":{"value":true},"longterm":{"value":true},"shortterm":{"value":true},"beliefs":{"value":true},"secret":{"value":true}},"scrollPos":"{\".tab.details .tab-inner\":0,\".tab.description .tab-inner\":0,\".relationships .items-list\":0}"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{"type":"person"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6nu2k3j5j03","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar Lore#/CF_SEP/Lhazaar Principalities#/CF_SEP/02.09.12. People#/CF_SEP/Potential Crew","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Q687UTK8tTH8uc8s","name":"Quarter Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Quarter Deck</h1>\n<p>This raised deck stands 15 feet above the main deck. The ship’s bridge is here and holds the ship’s wheel. The wheel is 3 feet across and has 10 spokes decorated with silver inlays, its bolts carved to resemble kraken heads.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#3598db\">Prince Rockface</span> and <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Mr. Lagraa </span>spend most of their time on this deck. When the captain is on deck, the poop deck and quarter deck are off-limits to everyone but officers.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_dljw0qnmnui","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"QygQfqdlw5zh5IkL","name":"Ship Punishments","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ship Punishments</h1>\n<p>To maintain the obedience and effectiveness of their crews, most captains enforce strict schedules and shipboard laws upon their vessels, all maintained by the swift dispensation of brutal punishments. The following presents (in order of severity) the game effects of a variety of typical nautical punishments, which the pirates have the potential to face or inflict during their piratical careers. Most of these sentences are meted out just before the evening meal, at an event typically referred to as the bloody hour. Victims are tied to the whipping post on the main deck and their backs stripped for punishment—with penalties doubled for those who resist. </p>\n<h3>Rope Bash</h3>\n<p>Little more than an admonishment—and occasionally used as a sign of endearment—a rope bash is a single attack with the hefty, sealed end of a ship’s rope.</p>\n<h3>The Lash</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a whip. Lashes during bloody hour require a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Vigor} check (+1) for every three lashes or cause one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p>\n<h3>Cat-o’-Nine-Tails</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a cat-o’-ninetails, also referred to simply as a cat—lashes with the cat require a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Vigor} check (–1) one level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} for every three strikes.</p>\n<h3>Confined in the Sweatbox</h3>\n<p>A cramped metal box left on deck and exposed to the sun, a sweatbox is terribly confining and replicates unbearably hot conditions. Each four hours in the sweatbox the victim must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Vigor} check or suffer a level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. There is a –1 to this check for each 8 hours they spend in the sweat box. Any creature with fire resistance is immune to the effects of the sweatbox. Victims typically spend 8, 12 or even 24 hours locked up in the sweatbox.</p>\n<h3>Keelhauling</h3>\n<p>The most frightful of pirate punishments is keelhauling, as it generally ends in death—often by decapitation. Being keelhauled involves being tied to a rope looped over a ship’s keel and dragged down one side of a ship, underwater across the barnacle encrusted hull, and up the other side. Keelhauling can be done either fast or slow. If done fast, the barnacles cut deep and flense the victim, dealing 2d6 points of damage per round. If done slow, shallower cuts are incurred, dealing 1d6 damage per round, but the risk of drowning increases. How long keelhauling takes typically depends on the vessel, with a keelhauling on a ship like the <em>Storm Reaver</em> taking 6 rounds if done fast and 12 rounds if done slow.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"}}}
