{"_id":"a5dWjtPnSBr1tjnt","name":"Ship Roles","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Ship Roles</h1>\n<p>All crew members on any ship have specific roles and responsibilities, often with harsh punishments being meted out upon those who shirk their duties. Listed here are some of the standard roles aboard a typical ship. Not all of these roles might be represented on every vessel, but such details can help players understand their characters’ daily duties.</p>\n<h2>Officers</h2>\n<h3>Captain</h3>\n<p>The ultimate authority on any ship responsible for the ship and everything aboard her, his word is law to all on board. The captain chooses where to sail, what are fitting punishments for breeches in discipline,  and who fills the other stations aboard the vessel, among many other command decisions. The captain is the voice of the crew to all beyond the ship. In terms of daily duties, the captain keeps a log of the voyage, manages the affairs of the ship through the officers, working with the navigator to plot courses, and generally serves a four to six hour shift at the helm. Leadership can prove perilous, however, as a captain is, above all, meant to secure success for his ship and crew. Failing to do so increases the threat of mutiny.</p>\n<h3>First Mate</h3>\n<p>The first mate is the number two man on the ship. She is responsible for enforcing the ship’s articles and administering punishment when necessary. The first mate is the trustee of the ship and her crew, often being elected by the crew to the position. She directly represents the crew to the captain. It is her responsibility to serve as a counterbalance to the captain in decisions that might be hazardous to the ship or the crew. A wise captain makes no decisions that his first mate doesn't support. The first mate takes responsibility for prize vessels and picks the treasure that the crew will take from a prize. She is also responsible for counting the booty and splitting the shares according to each crewmembers due. Each day will find her working with her subordinate officers the boatswain, the master gunner, and the master at arms to effectively run the ship. The first mate also serves a turn at the helm, generally a four to six hour shift.</p>\n<h3>Navigator</h3>\n<p>The navigator is responsible for plotting the ship’s course and maintaining that course, thus requiring an strong education and excellent all around seamanship. The navigator maintains all of the ship’s charts and maps as well as the tools of navigation. He is charged with keeping a daily log of every event relating to the sailing of the ship. He records the depth, the currents, the wind patterns, the ship’s location, the locations of reefs and sandbars, and the state of the rigging. He reports directly to the captain. The pilot oversaw the work of the sail-master and almost always has at least one assistant (a pilot’s mate) to help him with his duties. The pilot and his mate both serve separate shifts at the helm in addition to taking readings from the moons and stars to plot and maintain the course.</p>\n<h3>Boatswain</h3>\n<p>The boatswain, or bosun (pronounced “bosun” either way), is responsible for maintaining the ship's seaworthy status. This makes the boatswain accountable for all rope, rigging, anchors, and sails. His duties were to make certain that all the work of running the ship is done. This would also include keeping the watches and maintaining discipline among the deck crew. At the start of the day, the boatswain and those under her weigh anchor, raise the sails and report on the general condition of the ship’s deck to the first mate. The boatswain was often the most feared man on the ship because his obligations often made him uncompromising. It was his responsibility to keep everything “ship-shape”. Day and night, the boatswain drives the crew to do whatever work is required. He maintains the watch log and reports any problems to the first mate.</p>\n<h3>Coxswain</h3>\n<p>The coxswain (who could be a bosun’s mate and is pronounced 'cox’n') steered the ship (when he could be known as the helmsman) and was in charge of any small boats on board - useful for going ashore, exploring shallows, and boarding other vessels.</p>\n<h3>Quartermaster</h3>\n<p>The quartermaster oversees all the supplies and items stored aboard the ship. She maintains the supplies of food, water, sails, rope, wood, and tar, oversees the disbursement of food to the cook, and doles out the rum ration to the crew. The quartermaster also directs the loading of cargo into the hold to maintain the proper ballast to ensure level sailing.</p>\n<h3>Artificer/Mage</h3>\n<p>Many ships that ply the waters around Khorvaire have an artificer and/or mage on board. They can be responsible for the functioning of any magical locomotion of the ship, repairs, general arcane knowledge or any number of other magical needs the ship might have. They are also expected to contribute firepower or counter enemy magical firepower in any ship to ship conflicts that happen on the vessel. </p>\n<h3>Master-at-Arms</h3>\n<p>The Master at Arms is often the most skilled warrior on the crew. He is responsible for training the crew in hand to hand combat. He also leads the ship’s boarding parties and hunting parties when they are necessary. The Master at Arms position is not a separate position on every vessel and often these responsibilities fall to the first mate or quartermaster. When the master at arms position is filled on a ship, he takes orders from and reports to the first mate.</p>\n<h3>Master Gunner</h3>\n<p>The master gunner is in charge of all shipboard artillery, ensuring the weapons are kept in good working order, repaired, and that the crew knows how to use them. She maintains the ballistas, catapults, and so on. The master gunner picks, trains and runs the gunnery crew. He reports to the first mate, but was responsible to the entire ship to make sure the artillery hits the target. He day to day duties consists of drilling the gunnery crew and maintaining the weapons.</p>\n<h2>Crew</h2>\n<h3>Cabin Boy/Girl</h3>\n<p>Servant to the captain and other officers, this low-ranking and typically young crew member assists other sailors in their duties and runs various errands across the ship, requiring him or her to gain a measure of understanding of almost all the ship’s roles.</p>\n<h3>Carpenter</h3>\n<p>No matter what enchantments or alchemical unguents augment a pirate ship, its heart and bones are still wood. This simple fact makes the carpenter one of the most important positions aboard any vessel. Carpenters are chiefly responsible for maintaining the ship below the deck, finding and plugging leaks, repairing damage, and replacing masts and yards. Carpenters are also responsible for the construction of barrels and crates as necessary to store cargo. The carpenter reports to the boatswain.</p>\n<h3>Cook</h3>\n<p>While the quartermaster normally allocates the rations, the cook and his apprentices make and distribute meals to the crew. Although some better-outfitted vessels employ skilled cooks to attend to the captain and the officers, many cooks are drawn from crew members who have suffered crippling injuries, allowing them to still serve even after such trauma.The cook takes orders from either the quartermaster or the boatswain.</p>\n<p>Cooper</p>\n<p>A cooper was only found on board a larger vessel, but he was very useful as he could assemble barrels, a key skill because, at the time, these were the only large containers available and were used for keeping dry stores, wet stores, water, rum, and gunpowder in. He ensured they remained as airtight and watertight as possible, and he could dismantle empty barrels to increase space for newly captured cargo. The cooper also made and repaired buckets.</p>\n<h3>Healer</h3>\n<p>Many ships have a healer on board to tend to any injuries that happen. Whether this is a House Jorasco healer, Jorasco trained, or some herbalist with slight training in healing, depends on the vessel. The healer takes orders from the first mate.</p>\n<h3>Rigger</h3>\n<p>Riggers work the rigging and unfurl the sails. In battle, next to that of a boarding party, the riggers’ job is one of the most dangerous, as they pull enemy vessels near enough to board. Riggers report to the sail-master and the boatswain.</p>\n<h3>Sail-Master</h3>\n<p>The Sail-master is the most experienced crewman in the rigging and usually one of the best sailors on the ship. He is responsible for maintaining the sails and the rigging. The Sail-master knows every knot, line, rope, block and tackle in the rigging as well as how to repair them all. He is also responsible for training and running the sail crew as well as overseeing the making and patching of sails. The Sail-master takes orders from and reports to the navigator.</p>\n<h3>Sailmaker</h3>\n<p>Like the carpenter, blacksmith, and cooper, this was a specialist artisan job, and the man skilled at it need not necessarily know any other skills of seamanship. Sails were always worn down by weather, often ripped up by storms, and sometimes riddled to pieces by siege weapons or magic.</p>\n<h3>Swab</h3>\n<p>Any sailor who mops the decks. Also used as slang for any low-ranking or unskilled crew member.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_f5h8exvluwf","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Ship lore","color":"#000000"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"scrollPos":"{\".description\":0}"}}}
{"_id":"acDz3n4ZSmht0mKD","name":"Brig","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Brig</h1>\n<p>The main brig is two cells that have enough room to fit two people each if need be, however usually only one creature is held in each cell. At the start of the adventure two of the pirates wake up in one cell. In the other cell is Jakes Magpe awaiting his punishment.</p>\n<p>The manacles in each cell are average locks (–1 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} checks) and the locks on the cell doors are superior locks (–3 to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} checks).</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_dljw0qnmnui","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
