{"_id":"cIyrmqLZiiZ7f4La","name":"Morgana Verazzo","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p>Morgana was the quartermaster of the <em>Sovereign’s Folly</em>, the ship Daina fled Cyre on. She was turned off the ship in @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Sharn] like all of the Cyrans on board were when news of the Mourning reached them. Unlike all of the other Cyrans on board the Folly, Morgana refused to go to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.High Walls], and stayed on the docks instead looking for another ship to sail on. She was eventually given a berth on the <em>Last Horizon</em>, but whether or not she still sails on that ship, Daina has no idea.</p>\n<p>Morgana was with Daina on the <em>Sovereign's Folly</em> when the news reached them about the Mourning. The last time they saw each other was in mid-995 when Morgana crewed out on a ship called the <em>High and Low</em> transporting a Tharashk expedition to Q'barra. She later heard that the expedition had been recalled to Droaam, and that the <em>High and Low</em> had been attacked by the pirates in the waters between Lorghalen and Lastpoint. Rumour has it that they were rescued by the Grey Tide, and have been working for Prince Kel out of gratitude ever since.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/monks-enhanced-journal/assets/person.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"person","relationships":[],"role":"","location":"Last Known Location was sailing on the Last Horizon","race":"Khorvar","gender":"Female","age":"","pronoun":"She/Her","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"Quartermaster","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","_lasttab":"description","fields":{"race":{"value":true},"gender":{"value":true},"age":{"value":true},"eyes":{"value":true},"skin":{"value":false},"hair":{"value":true},"pronoun":{"value":true},"profession":{"value":true},"voice":{"value":true},"faction":{"value":false},"height":{"value":false},"weight":{"value":false},"traits":{"value":true},"ideals":{"value":false},"bonds":{"value":false},"flaws":{"value":true},"longterm":{"value":false},"shortterm":{"value":false},"beliefs":{"value":false},"secret":{"value":false}},"scrollPos":"{\".tab.details .tab-inner\":0,\".tab.description .tab-inner\":0,\".relationships .items-list\":0}"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{"type":"person"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6nu2k3j5j03","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar Lore#/CF_SEP/Lhazaar Principalities#/CF_SEP/02.09.12. People#/CF_SEP/Potential Crew","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"cLIR2HP5e20FbIy4","name":"Ghoul","content":"","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-bestiary/undead/ghoul-harlot.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_m6k8nmm3aib","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Images#/CF_SEP/Season 1","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"cacdPFb6F3YClNyq","name":"Main Deck","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Main Deck</h1>\n<p>The ship’s main deck runs between the foredeck and poop deck. The mainmast rises from the center of the deck, extending 60 feet into the air and topped by a crow’s nest. Rigging connects the mainmast to the ship’s other masts and can be crossed with DC 10 Acrobatics or Climb checks. Several strands of thick rope are secured to the foot of the mainmast for use as a whipping post. An Escape Artist check (DC 20 + the binder’s CMB) is required to escape the bonds. The ship’s clock, a macabre brass-and copper object depicting worms writhing through whale corpses, hangs from the mast above the whipping post. Not only does the clock keep time, but its bell strikes at dawn and dusk to signal the beginning and the end of the workday.</p>\n<p>Two 10-foot-square hatches sit in the deck fore and aft of the mainmast. These hatches are thick wooden grilles (hardness 5, hp 30, DC 25 Strength check to lift) and open onto the middle hold (area A6) 15 feet below. At the fore of the ship, two doors lead into the officers’ quarters (area A4), while two doors aft lead to the captain’s quarters (area A5). A large wooden box bound in iron sits just beneath the bridge. This sweatbox, used to torment sailors, has just enough room to hold one Medium creature (and can be altered to confine a Small creature). It is locked with a good lock (Disable Device DC 30); Prince Rockface and Mr. Plugg have the keys.</p>\n<p>A small jolly boat (same statistics as a rowboat) sits on the deck next to the port rail. It has two sets of oars but no mast. Although designed to carry four Medium passengers, the jolly boat can fit six at a push.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_dljw0qnmnui","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"dDyfNzqrtVqoM86r","name":"The Terror","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Terror</h1>\n<p>Ursa Ulm is searching for her father, Noran Nass, a master shipwright. He left under mysterious circumstances several months ago and hasn’t been heard from since. Ursa offers a bounty of $20,000 for her father’s return. The bounty is high because she has heard that it was the Emperor himself who spirited him away. A Streetwise roll at –4 proves she’s correct, and discovers that Noran was one of those “requested” to work on the Terror, the Great Whale’s new battle barge.</p>\n<p>The Terror lies in a deep bay on the island of Terras. It’s protected by two temporary gun emplacements with four guns each. The Terror’s guns can also be manned in an emergency.</p>\n<p>The marines, nine other shipwrights, and 73 workers live in a crudely built circular village on the beach. A dozen marines are always on board the Terror 50 yards offshore, a dozen guard the work details, and a dozen more patrol the island.</p>\n<p>If Noran is rescued, he offers to do a custom renovation on the heroes’ ship, increasing its base Toughness by 2 and its Travel Speed by 1. The others offer individual rewards worth 2d6 x $200.</p>\n<p>Marines (36): Typical Marines (p. 191).</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_slwk1t4xhcl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Savage Tales","color":"#000000"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"e8jhDVoMZBZ4P6hq","name":"Treasure for the Taking","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Treasure for the Taking</h1>\n<section class=\"secret gm-secret\">\n<p>Combine this with elements from Pirate's Bounty and the Isle of Fire Eberron Adventure.</p>\n</section>\n<p>“Stumpy” Pete, a regular at the Shipwreck Surprise, has two wooden legs (hence the name). Since being washed up on the island last year he has worked as Azy’s accountant— he’s not much use as a farmer or sailor. The locals suspect he has a hidden stash of treasure somewhere on the island but countless searches have revealed nothing.</p>\n<p>Stumpy approaches the group while they are drinking in the tavern. He invites them to join him for a drink and to partake in a business venture.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“Name’s Stumpy Pete,” he slurs, obviously the worse for drink. “Afore I came to the cay I was a pirate by trade working under a French corsair by the name of Pierre La Grange. He was small fry compared to some—at least until we found treasure.</p>\n<p>“While exploring an island north of the Whips we discovered a stash of treasure buried in a ruined building. We was only a small crew, just the ten of us, but we struck it rich beyond our wildest dreams. Gold, silver, and jewels in abundance just waiting for us to find it.</p>\n<p>“We took what we could carry and left the rest, planning on returning when we could. The captain said carrying too much would make us an easy target if other pirates found out. We spent most of our loot in Baltimus before heading to Shark Bay to acquire a larger ship. Never made it that far though. The ship sank in a storm somewhere off the coast of this island. I was lucky—I was washed up here. Lost my other leg but at least I’m alive.</p>\n<p>“I can tell you doubt my story and I don’t blame you. If you want some proof the treasure exists then look no further.” With that, he removes his right leg and holds it upside down over the table. A small bag slides out and lands with a soft clunk. Stumpy opens the bag to reveal two dozen small diamonds.</p>\n<p>“This is just a taste of what we found. I can’t trust these pirates to help me, but if you’ll take me to the island I’ll share the booty with you— fifty-fifty.”</p>\n</aside>\n</section>\n<p>No one on the island knows Stumpy has the gems—he exchanges them for coin with visiting crews. The treasure is real and the offer genuine. Hard bargaining and a raise on a Persuasion roll can increase the group’s share to 75% of the haul. The only thing “Stumpy” failed to mention was the horrible creature guarding the treasure—another reason he has never returned to the island.</p>\n<p>Stumpy Pete Pete lost his first leg to grapeshot and the second when he was shipwrecked off Azy Cay. He is content with his life on the Cay—he has a steady job, his own shack, and his booty goes further than it would in a big city. All he wants now is the rest of the treasure to see him through in comfort to his dying days. Attributes: @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Agility} d6, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Smarts} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Spirit} d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Strength} d6, Vigor d8 Skills: Boating d6, Climbing d8, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Fighting} d8, Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Swimming d6 Charisma: 0; Pace: 2; Parry: 6; Toughness: 6 Hindrances: Bad Luck, One Leg (twice—suffers –4 penalty to traits requiring mobility and cannot run), Stubborn Edges: Dirty Fighting, Fast Healer, Frugal, Harder to Kill, Rich Gear: Two pistols, crutches, cutlass (Str+d6).</p>\n<h2>Treasure Island</h2>\n<p>The island lies 70 miles due north of Kuwayway and does not appear on any charts—it’s simply too small. Rising steeply from the sea, the cliffs tower 100 feet above the surrounding water. Atop is a rugged plateau covered in dense forest. Aside from a small colony of monkapes and some razor wings the island is uninhabited. Actually that isn’t true—the Sea Hags know about the treasure and sent a guardian to watch over it. (See below for details.)</p>\n<p>Scaling the cliffs requires three Climbing rolls. Failure results in a drop of 1d6 x 5 yards. Stumpy can’t climb and must be winched to the top.</p>\n<p>After getting his bearings, Stumpy leads the group north through the forest. The short walk to the ruin involves crossing rugged ground and hacking through the forest—not to mention having to walk at Stumpy’s slow pace. Have everyone make Vigor rolls. A failure results in a level of Fatigue, recovered after 15 minutes rest.</p>\n<p>The ruin once served as a Kieran noble’s hunting retreat but fell into disuse after the Flood. The owner and servants are all dead— drowned in an attempt to cross the Flotsam Sea and reach the “safety” of Kiera. Thick vines cling to the walls and only the main entrance shows any sign of disturbance—this is where “Stumpy” and his crew entered last year.</p>\n<p>The treasure belonged to a pirate (now resting at the bottom of sea) who found the island several years ago and thought it a safe place to conceal his loot.</p>\n<p>Have the characters make Notice rolls. On a success, they realize Stumpy has grown very nervous, wringing his hands and glancing quickly from side to side. If questioned he says, “Strange being back that’s all. Reminds me of my dead shipmates. Come on, the loot’s in the ballroom. Let’s get it and go.”</p>\n<p>Stumpy leads the group to the ballroom and points to some flagstones in the far corner. The stones lift easily to reveal six chests, each full to bursting with treasure. Disturbing the chests alerts the Sea Hags’ guardian lurking in the forest nearby. It attacks as the group leaves the ruin.</p>\n<p> Guardian Beast: The guardian beast is actually a giant zombie monkape, placed here by the Sea Hags to guard the treasure. Use the statistics for a regular giant monkape (p. 192) but add the Fear, Fearless, and Undead Special Ability (as per a zombie). The beast concentrates its attacks on the character carrying the mummified head.</p>\n<p> Booty: Two King’s Ransoms. In addition there is a golden triangle engraved with strange writing and a wooden box containing a mummified head.</p>\n<h2>Mummified Head</h2>\n<p>The head is the true reason the Sea Hags sent a guardian to the island. It belonged to a powerful archmage who sacrificed his life to give the inhabitants of Caribdus a chance to defeat the three sisters. The head is alive—sort of—and can still use its magic. When the lid is lifted the eyes open and a disembodied voices speaks to the heroes, “My magic is yours to command but only against the three sisters.”</p>\n<p>It has 50 Power Points, a d12+2 Spellcasting, and knows every spell, but can only cast them in the final battles against the Sea Hags. Power Points are not recharged—once the last one is spent the head crumbles to dust.</p>\n<p>Neither the Hags nor their minions can touch the head or affect it with magic—hence the zombie monkape guardian.</p>\n<p>If the group has already defeated the Sea Hags the head is less powerful—it can teach a mage a single spell, ignoring the usual rank requirement. This takes 2d6 hours of instruction, after which the mage may add to spell to his repertoire. The head then crumbles to dust.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_4s6bxi84dvu","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Savage Tales#/CF_SEP/The Dragonshards","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"eltDYUweV0xcQduQ","name":"Risky Games in the Bilges","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Risky Games in the Bilges</h1>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_72m1iiovqki","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"fOqtQyLwwf8hbwG5","name":"Pirates of Cyre Characters","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Pirates of Cyre Characters</h1>\n<h2>Cyre is Destroyed!</h2>\n<p>Cyre is Destroyed! Gone! No one would help us after the Mournland rolled through. We were even forgotten from the negotiating table at the laughable Treaty of Thronehold. As well intended as Prince Oargev might be, New Cyre is on Brelish land. There no telling when the \"generosity\" of that throne (or the Parliment) will want their land back. There is little hope that the Mournland can be reversed. Even if it could, there is not enough Cyrans left to stop the rush of Karrns, Thranes, and Brelanders that would come in to take the land. </p>\n<p>If Cyre is to survive, you need to take matters into your own hands. You have lived your life on the sea for @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cyre]{Cyre}, so it's time to take what you know and see how you can support Cyre. Since nobody seems to care about Cyrans, maybe it is time to take what we can to give to those Cyrans who now have nothing. So now it is time to turn to piracy to help out the Cryans that survive. The @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Lhazaar Principalities]{Lhazaar Principalities} are too chaotic and disjointed now with the largest shipping lanes in Khorvaire after the loss of the Great Canal. It is time to take some of the wealth from those that have so much to help those that have lost so much. Who knows, with a kind eye from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Arawai]{Arawai}, and a blessing from @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.The Devourer]{the Devourer}, maybe you might acquire enough plunder and noteriety (or Infamy) to be able to claim some land or even a prinipality for the survivors of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Cyre]{Cyre}. </p>\n<h2>Campaign Intention</h2>\n<p>In the Pirates of Cyre campaign, you are going to take on the role of Cyrans who survived the Day of Mourning or those friendly and sympathetic to the Cyran plight. Fed up with how Cyrans are being treated by the other nations, you are choosing to use your life long knowledge of the sea, to turn to piracy.</p>\n<p>This campaign is intended to be a very pulpy and swashbuckling in nature. It will start off on some rails, but will open up into a large sand box that will be very much driven by you.</p>\n<p>Your reasons for turning to piracy could include any number of reasons. Here are some examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Prince Oargev, or someone who has his ear, has asked or planted a seed in you to use your skills in this manner to find a new home for Cyrans or at least send money to support New Cyre.</li>\n<li>Perhaps you fear that @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Breland]{Breland} will eventually kick Cyrans out of New Cyre and leave everyone you know and love left, once again homeless. You can change that.</li>\n<li>You are just plain bitter at any number of the other nations for what they did to Cyre. Either for unjustly starting the new war, what you see as war crimes during the war, shutting their doors to your people in thier time of greatest need, or something else. Regardless, you are only giving them what they deserve.</li>\n<li>You don't trust Prince Oargev to do right by Cyrans. He is too beholden to @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Breland]{Breland}, so you will take matters into your own hands to help yourselves, and any other Cyrans that can see what you are doing.</li>\n<li>You survived the Day of Mourning by being at sea, and have been here in the Lhazaar for a long time now. The law here is that you keep what you take. This has just finally started to rub off. Why not do this for Cyrans?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Regardless of your reasons, the most important thing to keep in mind when creating your character is that piracy plays a significant role in this campaign, and your character should be willing on some level to engage in it. Whether you are pirates with or without honor makes no difference. It also does not matter if you are just interested in plundering wealth just for self or for other Cyrans, raiding, overthrowing an existing prince, or finding land for a new home for Cyre. All these options have a place in this campaign, and you get to decide what that is. Outside of there being piracy, there is no intention to force you players into being a certian kind of pirate.</p>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":4},"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_sfbrzx24rkb","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Player Character Guide","color":"#000000"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}}}}
{"_id":"fitTepd1kSfxudlF","name":"05 Wrecked on Bonewreck Isle","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Wrecked on Bonewreck Isle</h1>\n<p>The two most likely places to land on @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Bonewreck Isle]{Bonewreck Isle} are near an abandoned fishing village on the northern shore or the beach to the east of the isle.</p>\n<h3>Through the Swamp</h3>\n<p>If the swabs land in the fishing village and then head through the Swamp they will encounter the Mire. This a place where a salt river oozes through the swamp forming a barrier of quicksand and marsh. Though the trees provide a means to cross the The renants of an old wooden bridge remain across the bog.</p>\n<p>Crossing this area is a dramatic task requiring 4 successes in 3 rounds per character. To complicate things gaint frogs will come out of the mud in round two trying to snatch some easy food.</p>\n<h3>Whores Boudoir</h3>\n<p>A terrible stench fills the swamp here, a fetid odor of cheap perfume and rotting flesh. A huge tree stands in the middle of a clearing in the swamp, draped with some sort of huge tent. Lurid, painted faces cover both the tree trunk and tent, and both are decorated with rotting humanoid body parts and carpets of squirming insects.</p>\n<p>This is the home of the three ghouls that have survived from the wreck of the <em>Infernus. </em>This is the remnants of a considerable tent that is lashed around a great tree. Clouds of flies dance around all the decay.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Ghoul]{Ghoul} (3)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Crab Palm Beach</h3>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Towering palm trees stretch along the white sand beach for a mile or so, each around 50 feet high and crowned with a wide canopy of palms brimming with coconuts.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>There are a number of normal coconut crabs inhabiting the beach. There are three crabs that have reached great size and live up in various trees on the beach. They might be interested in a fleshly looking meal.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Giant Crab]{Giant Crab} (3)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>The Fields</h3>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>A clearing in the jungle contains overgrown fields of some sort of corn. The crops have gone wild, creating a high barrier wafting gently in the breeze.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>The fields were planted by the cast away Arron Ivy in his first few days here. He was driven off by the ghouls and the crops grew wild and neglected. There is only one track through the cornfield, but it requires a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} check (–1) to find and follow. The cornfield has grown over 8 feet tall and provides concealment for those within it. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} check (–2) will see the occasional exposed jawbone or other skeletal remains. </p>\n<p>In several places Arron erected scarecrows topped with the heads of dead sailors to try and scare off the ghouls. This failed to work.  These heads are now infested with botflies, which swarm around the heads in black clouds. Creatures that tamper with the heads release a swarm of botflies.</p>\n<p>An Ankheg lurks beneath the soil in the farm.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Ankheg]{Ankheg} (1)</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Vermin Swarm (MBT)]{Botfly Swarm}</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Castaway's Stockade</h3>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>A well-built timber stockade surrounds a small lodge in a jungle clearing. Vines wrap and strangle a great tree that rises to the next lodge, blocking light from above it. Beside the tree is a bubbling spring.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>Arron Ivy constructed the stockade to protect himself from the ghouls. The stockade gate is ajar and the walls are made a sharpened wooden poles 7 feet high. The small spring is the only source of fresh water on the island.</p>\n<p>There is a weathered spyglass fixed onto the stockade wall. It is pointed at Riptide Cove. A @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} check will discover that the spyglass has been fixed to that particular position. Anyone looking through the spyglass will catch a glimpse of a pair of Grindylows playing in the cove. One of them is wearing Sandara Quinn's tricorne hat.</p>\n<h3>Stockade Lodge</h3>\n<p>The wooden door to the lodge is currently ajar. Inside is a single chamber, crowded with a large amount of furniture looted from the Infernus. It includes a comfortable bed, a small writing desk, cooking gear, and several barrels of rotting food. The stench of rot is overpowering and flies swarm within the room.  In the middle of the room, a stool lies knocked to the floor under a hooded corpse hanging from a chain off a beam in the middle of the room.</p>\n<p>Aaron Ivy hangs from the ceiling in a failed attempt to kill himself and stave off turning into a ghoul. Instead he turned into a ghast before he died. He is playing possum from the ceiling as he has heard fresh meet coming in. He has been unable to free himself. He will take the first opportunity available to try and use someone to set himself free. He needs a successful @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.SzVzIV8ZxqKg3Oe3]{Athletics} check to free himself. Once free he attacks anyone nearby, if unable to free himself, he lashes at anyone with his claws.</p>\n<p>The decay has also drawn a swarm of botflies which also attack any living creature that disturbs Ivy.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Ghast]{Ghast}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Vermin Swarm (MBT)]{Botfly Swarm}</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Wreck of the  Infernus</h3>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>The rotting hulk of a wrecked ship lays in a bed of coral just off the shore in the clear shallow water.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>The wreck of the Karrn scout ship Infernus lies on a reef in shallow water here, some 20 feet below the surface at low tide.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/ambience/nautical/tropical-island-shoreline-02.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_n10pg472em","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers","color":"#000000"}}}
