,"3hooq1e9mFdU5dNB","mc3yxNeDEjdgPFMu","Vih1K90gKmHX1Qsa","jaCfiP0NV7KRc1K9","Q687UTK8tTH8uc8s","rnJBvK2yrMvpvfAx","9vVuPgzUZDmBtiAw","v4w8i8JJjzYB75fO"]},"FDc8OuXwl18j9XWe","uBLRsS3lJKLrI2XW","XnKy6uYwlpOoOiu1","JBrneClXhXYT5ZGX","wNrPtS4Qh7lC6lfr"],"icon":null,"path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver","parent":"temp_n10pg472em","contents":["FDc8OuXwl18j9XWe","uBLRsS3lJKLrI2XW","XnKy6uYwlpOoOiu1","JBrneClXhXYT5ZGX","wNrPtS4Qh7lC6lfr"]},{"id":"temp_72m1iiovqki","folderPath":["temp_bmn52t4oyo","temp_n10pg472em"],"color":"#000000","fontColor":"#FFFFFF","name":"The Storm Reaver Savage Tales","children":["Sc8zngwHZvU5mmmY","0her9fqDEQGD0sd0","s9fyLkRMd21SgmaD","eltDYUweV0xcQduQ","8579PWn4dLL6v9kV","rOIFr1FLjz0CznqP","j8zYeeugTzUe2HdO"],"icon":null,"path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver Savage Tales","parent":"temp_n10pg472em","contents":["Sc8zngwHZvU5mmmY","0her9fqDEQGD0sd0","s9fyLkRMd21SgmaD","eltDYUweV0xcQduQ","8579PWn4dLL6v9kV","rOIFr1FLjz0CznqP","j8zYeeugTzUe2HdO"]},"OFdQGATN7TtJNvRX","U6QtUVBcJ3kCOUrn","Unf9BdNknxxW8NJc","276jgwCRrWKYcf0I","fitTepd1kSfxudlF","jFJFL5sly5U5OGOF"],"folderPath":["temp_bmn52t4oyo"]}}}
{"_id":"rKPiCQNSPMP0Upo8","name":"The Black Prince","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Black Prince</h1>\n<p>This adventure can be run in place of any encounter at sea.</p>\n<p>Night falls and a heavy fog rises, forcing the heroes’ ship to slow to a crawl. Even the powerful storm lanterns do little to illuminate the murky gloom. The thick fog muffles the sound of the ship carving through the dark water, and only the faint creaking of timbers breaks the eerie silence.</p>\n<p>Read the following when one or more characters are on watch—preferably when they are alone.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Although the night is far from warm, you feel the air around you grow noticeably colder. The sudden chill causes you to shiver involuntarily. The hairs on the back of your neck rise and you get the distinct feeling someone is standing behind you—someone who wasn’t there a few seconds ago. A faint whiff of decay reaches your nostrils, causing you to gag.</p>\n</aside>\n</section>\n<p>If the character tries to ignore the strange sensations, the feeling of unease grows steadily stronger. Eventually one of the crew happens by and screams out, pointing behind the character.</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Standing an arm’s length behind you is a ghastly figure who glows with a cold, pale blue light. It is dressed in the fashion of a Spanish naval captain from the late 18th century, though his clothes appear ragged and worn. Maggots crawl through grisly wounds in its rotting flesh. With a ghastly moan, the figure raises its arm and points at you.</p>\n<p>“I need you,” it hisses in broken English. “You must help me.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Seeing the ghostly Spaniard calls for a Fear check. Attacking the figure is futile—weapons pass straight through without effect. No matter what the heroes do, the figure just stands on the deck, pointing at the nearest character. Seeing as the ghost makes no threatening gestures, and no doubt wishing it gone, striking a conversation should seem a sensible course of action.</p>\n<h2>The Ghost’s Tale</h2>\n<p>Assuming the party converses with the spirit, it tells its sorrowful tale:</p>\n<section class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>“My name is Captain Iago Alfonso de Toledo,” he says, his voice resonating in the still air. “I was captain of the Black Prince, a Spanish galleon brought into this world three years ago. My ship arrived in the midst of a terrible storm and floundered. The crew abandoned ship and set out in the longboats. A higher authority had already sealed our fate, for we found no land and one by one my crew died of thirst. Rather than suffer, I threw myself overboard and drowned.</p>\n<p>“Since that day I have wandered as a spirit, unable to find peace. In order to depart to whatever fate awaits me, I must have the locket my wife gave me. Without it I am lost, trapped between existences.</p>\n<p>“I cannot journey beneath the waves, but I can aid you in reaching my ship. She lies a day’s sail from here, on a shelf 20 fathoms deep. Aid me and the treasures my ship carried are yours for the taking.”</p>\n</section>\n<p>Captain Iago seems sincere, but hides a terrible secret—when his vessel sank it was carrying slaves to the Americas. No attempt was made to rescue the slaves, and Iago was cursed to wander Caribdus as a ghost until he found someone to aid him.</p>\n<h2>Reaching the Wreck</h2>\n<p>As Iago stated, the wreck of his ship lies a day’s sail from the party’s present location. Iago can pinpoint its location with supernatural accuracy.</p>\n<p>The wreck lies in 20 fathoms of water, on the bottom of a shelf. Getting down to the wreck without the use of the environmental protection power is next to impossible. Luckily, Iago can imbue characters with the power simply by touching them. Unfortunately, he cannot extend the duration beyond an hour. Travel to and from the wreck takes a total of 20 minutes, leaving the group 40 minutes to explore.</p>\n<p>Although the power lets heroes move at their full Pace, armor still subtracts its protection value from Swimming rolls underwater. Leather armor also weighs twice as much when wet (which may affect encumbrance totals).</p>\n<p>As the characters make their descent, have them make sight based Notice rolls. Those who succeed spot maneater sharks (one per 2 heroes), darting toward the group out of the murky depths.</p>\n<p> Maneater Sharks (1 per 2 Heroes): p. 200.</p>\n<h2>The Black Prince</h2>\n<p>The ship suffered badly during the storm—the bow has shattered, its timbers dispersed over a wide area, leaving only the stern remaining. Rusty cannons and cannonballs lie in the silt where they fell. Entrance to the ship can be gained through the mid-section, which lies open. The name of the ship is no longer visible. Aside from the following areas, there is nothing of value on the vessel.</p>\n<p>Hold: Within the hold are the remains of 30 slaves, each manacled to the wall by a heavy chain. One of the skeletons is considerably larger than the others—this is the remains of Benga Mamoto’s brother, Machawi.</p>\n<p> Booty: Benga rewards the group with a charm bracelet if the skeleton is returned to him. The bracelet protects the wearer from evil spirits and grants +2 Armor against supernatural or magical attacks.</p>\n<p>Iago’s Cabin: Much of the furnishings remain, including the captain’s tarred sea chest. The corpses of several crewmembers lie on the floor, their tattered flesh food for numerous fishes.</p>\n<p> Zombies (1 per Hero): p. 203.</p>\n<p> Booty: The chest contains charts and papers, a silver portrait containing a miniature portrait of a dark haired woman, and 500 pieces of eight.</p>\n<p>Opening the chest underwater ruins the captain’s charts and papers. If kept dry, the papers reveal Iago’s business transactions, detailing slave shipments over many years and listing as many as 50% casualties among his cargo on some voyages. The charts are useless, showing the Americas rather than Caribdus, but are worth $200 to a collector such as Jose-Maria Caballeros (page 88).</p>\n<p>If the heroes try to leave with the locket—in or out of the chest—the corpses animate as zombies. Iago’s crew, subjected to the torment of being undead, has no wish for their captain to find salvation.</p>\n<h2>Redemption</h2>\n<p>Once the heroes return to their ship, Iago rushes up to them, demanding the locket and making all manner of threats if refused. Fortunately for the heroes he cannot harm them (part of his curse), nor can he take the locket by force—it must be given to him freely.</p>\n<p>Whether or not the characters hand over the locket is a personal choice. Iago willfully and knowingly left his “cargo” to die when his ship floundered, thus bringing the curse on himself and his crew.</p>\n<p>If the locket is handed over, Iago clutches it to his chest, thanks the heroes, and vanishes, never to be seen again. Should they refuse, Iago emits an anguished cry and fades from view, vowing revenge in the next life. Iago is tied to his ship but not the locket—a particularly cruel revenge is to sail away and throw the locket overboard at some random point in the journey, forever denying him peace.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"cf":{"id":"temp_slwk1t4xhcl","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"rOIFr1FLjz0CznqP","name":"The Storm on the Storm Reaver","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">The Storm</h1>\n<p>After a day of heavy winds and rain, a storm well and truly hits the <em>Storm Reaver</em> on the seventh day. The ship is tossed about on the high seas and all hands are called on deck to work, including the cook’s mate. All of the crew is required in the rigging, and the swabs are assigned random tasks from the rigger task list. All checks are made at a –2 penalty from the rain, sleet and ice. The crew must stay up all night battling the storm—there is no evening rest or entertainment, and after the evening meal (ship’s biscuit only, on this occasion), assign the PCs new tasks from the @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-tables.Rigging Tasks]{rigging tasks table}. The swabs must make @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Vigor} checks (–2 from the weather) to avoid becoming fatigued at the end of their second shift; swabs who take on a third level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue} become exhausted and drop to sleep at work, an act that earns them each six lashes the following day as punishment.</p>\n<p>At some point during the storm, a friendly pirate (your choice, but not Krornik Kragshard or Sandara Quinn) goes overboard. Swimming in stormy waters to reach the <em>Storm Reaver</em> is a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Task}. Only @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} may be used at a –1 penalty. This is a difficult dramatic task requiring 6 Task Tokens in four rounds or the swab is lost at sea.</p>\n<p>When the night shift ends, the next day’s work begins, and new tasks are assigned using the normal task tables. The swabs must make a @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Traits]{Vigor} (–1) to avoid taking on another level of @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{fatigue}.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_72m1iiovqki","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"rnJBvK2yrMvpvfAx","name":"Quartermasters Store","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Quartermasters Store</h1>\n<p>The ship’s quartermaster, <span style=\"color:#3598db\">@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Cut-Throat Grok]{Cut-Throat Grok}</span>, can usually be found in this cramped, crowded storeroom containing numerous barrels, boxes, and chests. The door is locked with a superior lock (@Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check –4, Grok has the key). <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grok </span>also has the key to the store room in the Galley that also has a superior lock.</p>\n<p>The quartermaster’s store acts as a kind of unofficial shop aboard the <em>Storm Reaver</em>. While any plunder stored there technically belongs to the captain, this is a pirate ship after all, and everything has its price. Any equipment stored within is for sale at the normal price listed.</p>\n<p>Items found on the ship (or won from other pirates) can also be traded at the store for other merchandise. Bartered objects are generally worth 50% of their normal value when traded for goods.</p>\n<p>While the store is, in theory, open at all hours, it’s usually only open from dawn to about 3 p.m., when <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grok </span>starts drinking. She only opens the door outside these hours to friends. <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grok </span>has a tendency to get drunk in the afternoons and closes the store before heading to the deck for the evening meal. After supper, <span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grok </span>carries the crew’s rum rations in a bucket to the main deck. She often forgets to lock the door or the hatch at this time, an oversight that occurs 75% of the time.</p>\n<h3>Store Room Treasure</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color:#3598db\">Grok </span>knows the value of the majority of the items in the store, but she is unaware of the value of those items marked with asterisks or thinks they are mundane, and sells or barters those items at their standard list prices. At the start of the adventure, the swabs’ starting equipment is held in one of the lockers, as described below. </p>\n<p><em><strong>Wooden Locker</strong> (simple lock, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check, no trap):</em> Contains a random selection of mundane adventuring gear with a value of 10 gp or less.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Wooden Locker</strong> (simple lock, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check, no trap):</em> Contains the swabs’ equipment, <span style=\"color:#3598db\">@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Rosie Cusswell]{Rosie Cusswell's}</span> masterwork fiddle, a tangat, 3 flasks of acid, 6 flasks of alchemist’s fire, four sets of thieves tools (one of which is masterwork*), and a battered iron box containing six candles, one of which is a candle of truth*.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Wooden Chest</strong> (broken lock, arrow trap):</em> Contains a potion of barkskin, a potion of cure light wounds, a minor potion of speed, a masterwork climber’s kit, a disguise kit, 4 flasks of holy water, a magnifying glass, a set of manacles, and two tanglefoot bags.</p>\n<h3>Storage Room Treasure</h3>\n<p>The store room contains 4 tuns of rum (each holding about 100 gallons of rum at the start of the journey).</p>\n<p><em><strong>Wooden Chest </strong>(average lock, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check (–1), arrow trap):</em> Contains a masterwork light crossbow, three cutlasses, 31 daggers, three masterwork daggers, 43 masterwork darts, four saps, a masterwork sap, 120 arrows, 20 masterwork arrows, six arrows of accuracy, and 200 crossbow bolts</p>\n<p><em><strong>Wooden Trunk</strong> (good lock, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check (–2), no trap):</em> Contains a suit of banded mail, a breastplate, two chain shirts, masterwork leather armor, three suits of studded leather armor, 12 bucklers, two masterwork bucklers, and a small cash box containing 231 cp, 99 sp, and 103 gp.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Metal Trunk</strong> (good lock, @Compendium[savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check (–2), poisoned dart trap): </em>Contains a +1 animal bane dagger* (Grok thinks this is just a normal +1 dagger), a +1 short sword, a masterwork warhammer, scrolls of major healing, mage armor, magic missile, scorching ray, and summon swarm, and a wand of havoc (16 charges).</p>\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L91WkUzg75E8tVjM"},"cf":{"id":"temp_dljw0qnmnui","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver#/CF_SEP/Locations on the Storm Reaver","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"s9fyLkRMd21SgmaD","name":"Laying Down the Law","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Laying Down the Law</h1>\n<p>Mere seconds after the bell tolls to summon the crew on deck, five pirates—@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Jaundiced Sudak]{Jaundiced Sudak}, @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Maheem]{Maheem},@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sador Chumlett]{Sador Chumlett},@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Slippery Syl]{Slippery Syl}, and @Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate]{Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate}—block the PCs’ path.</p>\n<aside class=\"read-aloud\">\n<p>Mere seconds after the bell tolls to summon the crew on deck, five pirates, four men and a woman block your path up to the main deck. A orc with a nasty scar over his left eye, dark skinned human with a scowl, a female dwarf that seems to be slick with sweat, a yellowed orc with yellow tinted eyes, and a stocky dwarf with a large ugly nose.</p>\n<p>“In a hurry?” one says, and laughs, pushing a random swab in the chest.</p>\n</aside>\n<p>Master Scourge has already talked to the five, telling them he doesn’t like these new swabs, and that the sluggards need to be knocked into shape. Scourge has instructed the pirates to give the PCs a bit of a beating and prevent them from getting on deck in time for their shift. The pirates want a fistfight, not a knife fight, and approach the PCs without weapons drawn. Meanwhile, a handful of other sailors loiter on the stairs to watch the fight.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Jaundiced Sudak]{Jaundiced Sudak}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Maheem]{Maheem}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Sador Chumlett]{Sador Chumlett}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Slippery Syl]{Slippery Syl}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary.Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate]{Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate}</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"aftermath\">Aftermath</h2>\n<p>If any character is killed, Mr. Lagraa launches an investigation, and keelhauls the murderer. <em>Any swabs</em> who arrive late on deck are sentenced to three lashes for laziness. Mr. Lagraa adds three more lashes if they are impertinent.</p>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-journal":{"_viewcount":1},"quick-encounters":{"quickEncounter":"{\"journalEntryId\":\"MMMTZcygBDdHuIMw\",\"extractedActors\":[{\"numActors\":1,\"dataPackName\":\"savage-tales-pirates-of-cyre.pirates-of-cyre-bestiary\",\"actorID\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"name\":\" Krornik Kragshard\",\"savedTokensData\":[],\"generatedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}],\"combinedTokensData\":[{\"actorId\":\"KEeR7YOKnWikm2I1\",\"isSavedToken\":false}]}],\"hideQE\":true,\"qeVersion\":\"0.8.4\"}"},"cf":{"id":"temp_72m1iiovqki","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar#/CF_SEP/Season 1: Mutiny Against the Cloudreavers#/CF_SEP/The Storm Reaver Savage Tales","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"sGCGr3tj9DG3T2F1","name":"Alexei Aarland","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<p> </p>\n</div>","img":"modules/monks-enhanced-journal/assets/person.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"monks-enhanced-journal":{"type":"person","relationships":[],"scrollPos":"{\".tab.details .tab-inner\":0,\".tab.description .tab-inner\":0,\".relationships .items-list\":0}","role":"Potential First Mate","location":"Unknown","race":"","gender":"Male","age":"","pronoun":"He/Him","eyes":"","skin":"","hair":"","profession":"Captain","voice":"","faction":"","height":"","weight":"","traits":"","ideals":"","bonds":"","flaws":"","longterm":"","shortterm":"","beliefs":"","secret":"","_lasttab":"details"},"_document-sheet-registrar":{"type":"person"},"journal-backlinks":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_6nu2k3j5j03","path":"Mourners of Lhazaar Lore#/CF_SEP/Lhazaar Principalities#/CF_SEP/02.09.12. People#/CF_SEP/Potential Crew","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"sQwxd7oG3u2NxVnn","name":"Defend the Village","content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\">\n<h1 class=\"wide\">Defend the Village</h1>\n<p>Finding Cuna woefully lacking in booty, the pirates gave the locals two days to gather food and timber for their return. Unwilling to bow to threats any longer the villagers convened a meeting and decided to seek help from any friendly ship arriving before the pirates return.</p>\n<p>The Harbor Master, Dominic Cooper, informs the party of the situation and pleads for assistance. He asks the heroes to help erect a wooden fence around the village, donate a cannon (with powder and ammunition), and help drive off the pirates in return for as much food and timber as they can spare and free Harbor Master stamps on any cargo they buy here for the next 12 months.</p>\n<p>Building the Wall: Of the 150 or so villagers, half are available to help work on the fence. Unfortunately the village has little prepared timber. In order to build the fence, trees must be felled and cleaned of branches, holes must be dug, and the logs sharpened and embedded in the ground—and all in two days.</p>\n<p>A fence completely surrounding the village requires 600 yards of wall. One character should be nominated as foreman. He must make a Persuasion roll each day—the villagers do not respond well to Intimidation—with a +2 bonus for each Leadership Edge he possesses. Each success and raise gathers 100 yards of sharpened timbers.</p>\n<p>Use the map on page 122 and let the defenders decide where to place the fence sections. The villagers place barrels on their side of the wall as firing platforms.</p>\n<h3>Here They Come!</h3>\n<p>The pirates’ brigantine anchors 90 yards offshore at dawn on the third day. The pirate captain isn’t blind—he sees the newly-erected fence and prepares his cannons accordingly. The range to the fence is 120 yards. If the group has left their ship in the harbor the captain orders his gunners to attack it while the raiding party goes ashore.</p>\n<p>A small fleet of longboats carries the pirates to shore. Once on land, the captain calls on the villagers to surrender or pay the price for disobedience—the total destruction of Cuna. No villager is prepared to negotiate with the pirates leaving a winner-takes-all fight as the only possible outcome.</p>\n<p>The distance between the beach and the fence is 20 yards. Climbing the fence requires a successful Climbing roll and takes an entire round. Firing over the fence provides Heavy Cover (–4).</p>\n<p>If the pirates lose ten men the captain orders a retreat back down the beach to take shelter behind their longboats while signaling his ship to open fire on the palisade. The fence has a Toughness of 11(2). Each wound the cannons cause creates a 2-yard (1 game inch) breach in the wall at a location of the Game Master’s choosing.</p>\n<p>After two volleys of cannon fire the pirates surge forth again, this time continuing the fight until the captain is killed or there are only ten left, at which point they return to their ship and sail away to lick their wounds. They do not return to Cuna again.</p>\n<p>Assuming the heroes have left crew on their ship they can use it to harass the pirates’ vessel. Commanding the pirate vessel is a Veteran Pirate—he has 12 Typical Pirates at his disposal.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Villagers (150):</span> Use Citizen stats (p. 184) with Fighting d4. Each villager has a pitchfork or shovel (Str+d4) plus any firearms the group can spare shared between them.</li>\n<li><span class=\"list-heading\">Pirates (41):</span> Typical Pirates and one Pirate Captain (p. 195). In addition to any other booty the captain has a golden triangle in his jacket.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","img":"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-adventures/pirates-of-cyre/icons/pirates-of-cyre.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"monks-enhanced-j